Brain Tumor Detection¶

Summary¶

This project presents a deep learning-based solution for brain tumor detection and segmentation using annotated MRI images. Leveraging a dataset from Hugging Face’s DWb2023 repository, it demonstrates strong performance in both pixel-wise segmentation and tumor classification. The model achieves over 99% classification accuracy and a 0.7 Intersection over Union (IoU) for bounding box localization. Visualizations comparing model predictions against ground truth masks highlight the network’s effectiveness in identifying and segmenting tumor regions.

Introduction¶

This project is a collaborative effort between Christopher Kinder and Humberto Potes aimed at developing a robust neural network for medical image analysis. The dataset used, titled "Brain Tumor Image Dataset for Semantic Segmentation", is sourced from Hugging Face’s DWb2023 repository. It comprises high-resolution MRI scans of brain tumors, with associated segmentation masks, bounding boxes, and class labels, supporting both localization and classification tasks.

The dataset is split into 1,502 training images and 429 validation images. To improve generalization and robustness, several data augmentation techniques are applied during preprocessing, including random rotations, horizontal/vertical flips, and brightness adjustments. These transformations help simulate variability found in real-world clinical data.

A custom, U-Net-inspired, multi-headed convolutional neural network is designed and trained to perform both pixel-wise segmentation and binary classification of tumor types. For clarity and clean presentation, the notebook provides a simplified overview focused on demonstrating general usage and results. The full implementation, including detailed training logic, mask post-processing, metric implementation, and evaluation procedures, is available in the accompanying GitHub repository through organized Python scripts. While the notebook serves as a high-level guide, the repository contains the complete codebase for reproducing and extending the project.

# Find the rows with the biggest and smallest areas
area_rows = df.loc[[df['area'].idxmax(), df['area'].idxmin()]]

# Extract the images and segmentation masks
images = [row['image'] for _, row in area_rows.iterrows()]
segmentations = [np.array(row['segmentation'][0]).reshape(-1, 2) for _, row in area_rows.iterrows()]
areas = area_rows['area'].values
titles = [f"Biggest Area: {areas[0]:.2f}", f"Smallest Area: {areas[1]:.2f}"]

# Plot the images with segmentation masks
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12, 6))

for ax, image, segmentation, title in zip(axes, images, segmentations, titles):
    ax.imshow(image)
    ax.plot(segmentation[:, 0], segmentation[:, 1], color='r', linewidth=2, label='Segmentation Mask')
    ax.set_title(title)
    ax.axis('off')
    ax.legend()

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

This visualization shows that the dataset contains mistakes in the segmentation masks, which can affect model performance. However, cleaning the dataset is not the focus of this project and requires expert knowledge in medical imaging, thus the model is trained on the provided data as-is.

Network¶

Quick overview of the custom neural network architecture used for the project. The model is inspired by U-Net, featuring an conv2d and conv2dtranspose structure with skip connections to preserve spatial information. It includes multiple heads for segmentation and classification tasks, allowing simultaneous prediction of tumor masks and types. Full details of the architecture, including layer configurations and activation functions, are available in model.py.

In [51]:
net = ConvTumorDetector(in_channels=1, num_classes=1)

Results¶

Visualization of Predictions¶

Here, we visualize the results of the trained model by loading a sample from the dataset and utilizing a pre-trained model saved at a specified path. The model processes the sample to generate predictions, including segmentation masks and classification labels, which are then compared against the ground truth for evaluation.

In [ ]:
dataset = load_dataset("dwb2023/brain-tumor-image-dataset-semantic-segmentation")
batch_size = 2

# load the training dataset
train_dataset = BrainTumorDataset(dataset['train'], augment=True)
train_loader = DataLoader(train_dataset, batch_size=batch_size, shuffle=True)

for first_image, first_mask, first_cat in train_loader:
    break

# Insert your saved model path here
model_path = "logs/model_epoch_150.pth"
net.load_state_dict(torch.load(model_path))
net.eval() 

with torch.no_grad():
    prediction, pred_cat = net(first_image)

# Prepare data for visualization
image_np = first_image.squeeze().cpu().numpy()
ground_truth_masks = first_mask.squeeze().cpu().numpy()

predicted_cat = sigmoid_to_binary(pred_cat, threshold=0.5)
predicted_labels = clean_by_distance(prediction, threshold=0.5)

The best model performance was observed between epochs 70 and 100, depending on the specific objective. At epoch 74, the model achieved a classification accuracy of 99.5% and an IoU of 0.707 for bounding box localization, demonstrating strong results in both tumor detection and segmentation tasks.

Conclusions¶

This project demonstrates a strong baseline for brain tumor detection and segmentation using a custom multi-headed convolutional neural network. With high classification accuracy and reliable mask predictions, it highlights the potential of deep learning in medical imaging. Future improvements could include using more advanced architectures, reducing false positives with better post-processing, and incorporating expert-led manual data cleaning.
